snippet.textDisplay:
There are apparently a LOT of people who don't know what a roast is.. "he is just stating the facts".. well.. If it is a roast it HAS to be something that at the very least can be ARGUED to be true.. but you use hyperbole, or something else to present it in an absurd light.. It is not actual "jokes", but a humorous way of presenting something so bad in such a way that people realize it isn't really meant to hurt anyone. . We can argue whether this was meant to hurt or not, because to me it seems fairly obvious that Gervais himself has some issues (anger? contempt of others? narcissism?)..

Sometimes I find Gervais to be funny, but quite often I think I find him rather lacking of actual emotional response and just project outward (a good humorist and satirist should to some extent "comfort" the audience in one way or another if there is starting to get too much tension in the room so it can't be enjoyed)..

Gervais himself isn't exactly someone who should claim to be living in the real world.

Of course.. I don't really say there is something "wrong" with this, I am probably just as jaded and as much of a "cranky old man" who doesn't properly "sense the room" to adjust for maximum impact... so.. I Am not trying to compete.. just.. no.. I don't agree he is so much to look up to as some of you think.. nor do I think he is so much to look down on as some other thinks..

But I do think he was not doing a good "job" here.. neither as a satirist, nor a political commentator.. But then again.. that is MY view.. and from the audience's reaction I'd say it was VERY mixed.. and I think they would've had better "results" with someone else.
